%N A396792 Maximum number of parts K in a partition of n such that there exists a part size p whose multiplicity is exactly p*K/100.
%C A396792 This sequence was inspired by the following puzzle from the book Mathematical Puzzles and Curiosities. If you choose the answer to this question at random, what is the probability you will be correct? A:25%, B:50%, C:60%, D:25%.
%C A396792 If we look at the answer options as a partition, this sequence finds the largest number of parts possible in a partition of n such that there exists a number p, with the property that if you choose a part uniformly at random in that partition, a part p will be chosen with probability p%. In other words, we are looking at partitions such that at least one answer can be considered correct.
%C A396792 For n >= 257, we have the following two cases: a(n) = 50*floor(n/51) when n is not equal to 1 modulo 51; otherwise, a(n) = 50*(floor(n/51)-1).
%D A396792 I. David, T. Khovanova, and Y. Shpilman, Mathematical Puzzles and Curiosities, World Scientific, 2026.
%e A396792 a(19) = 10. The maximizing partition has K=10 parts: one part of size 10 (which occurs exactly 10*10/100 = 1 time), and nine parts of size 1. The total number of values in the partition is 10 + 9*1 = 19.
%Y A396792 Cf. A000041, A276429, A392745, A394246, A394247, A392924.
